-- Ruble Strengthens to Dollar as U.S. Nears Debt Ceiling Deadline
-- B y   V l a d i m i r   K u z n e t s o v
-- 2013-10-16T11:03:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-10-16/ruble-strengthens-to-dollar-as-u-s-nears-debt-ceiling-deadline.html
The ruble strengthened against the
dollar as investors wagered the U.S. will reach a budget deal.  The ruble advanced 0.2 percent against the dollar to
32.2405 and traded little changed against Bank Rossii’s target
basket of dollars and euros at 37.3831 by 2:43 p.m. in Moscow.
The yield on the government’s February 2027 bonds declined one
basis point, or 0.01 percentage point, to 7.72 percent.  U.S. Senate leaders are resuming talks to lock down an
agreement to end the fiscal impasse. U.S. borrowing authority
lapses tomorrow, and  Fitch Ratings  placed the U.S.’s AAA credit
rating on negative watch. Crude oil, Russia’s main export
earner, was little changed at $101.27 a barrel in  New York .  “There’s no turmoil,” Anton Zakharov, a  money manager  at
OAO Promsvyazbank in Moscow, said in e-mailed comments. “It’s
too early to give up on the greenback.”  The ruble was little changed against the euro at 43.6705.
An index of 20 emerging countries currencies, compiled by
Bloomberg, fell 0.2 percent to 94.6709.  The  Finance Ministry  sold 14.7 billion rubles ($456
million) of bonds due August 2023 at an average yield of 7.49
percent out of 15 billion rubles offered, according to a
statement on the ministry’s website. A further 20 billion rubles
of debt maturing in 2018 is due to be offered in a separate
auction today.  “The  bond market  is calm,” Dmitry Dorofeev, a fixed
income strategist at BCS Financial Group in Moscow, said in e-mailed comments. “People are not ready to take the U.S. default
idea seriously yet.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
